The greatest terror prevailed in the city. The women fiocked to the temples to pray, while their husbands and sons manned the walls. It happened that two newly-raised legions were in the city. The consul hur- ried up from Capua with a great part of his army, aud the Albans sent a force to assist. Hannibal was unable therefore to do any thing but ravage the surrounding country and retire. The description Livy gives of the state of the city and the conduct of the women accounts for Juvenal taking this in- cident for his illustration. The route that Hannibal took from Capua to Rome is un- certain. It is generally supposed he came round to the north of the city, where he encamped within four miles of the walls. The porta Collina was the northern gate, that by which the Gaulsare said to have entered. 292.
